docs.abstract: We cannot forget what happened at Jackson State College in 1970, and the injustice that followed.
docs.snippet: We cannot forget what happened at Jackson State College in 1970, and the injustice that followed.
docs.lead_paragraph: JACKSON, Miss. — In the 1960s, white motorists driving along John R. Lynch Street, which cut through the middle of the historically black campus of what was then called Jackson State College, would often taunt students along the way with racist epithets, throw objects at them and threaten to hit pedestrians.

headline.main: 50 Years Ago, Police Fired on Students at a Historically Black College

docs.abstract: Mr. Trump has presented himself as someone who seeks conflict, not conciliation, a fighter, not a peacemaker. And he has lived up to his self-image at a perilous time.
docs.snippet: Mr. Trump has presented himself as someone who seeks conflict, not conciliation, a fighter, not a peacemaker. And he has lived up to his self-image at a perilous time.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — With a nation on edge, ravaged by disease, hammered by economic collapse, divided over lockdowns and even face masks and now convulsed once again by race, President Trump’s first instinct has been to look for someone to fight.

headline.main: In Days of Discord, a President Fans the Flames

docs.abstract: Scenes from a country in free fall.
docs.snippet: Scenes from a country in free fall.
docs.lead_paragraph: The last two and a half months in America have felt like the opening montage in a dystopian film about a nation come undone. First the pandemic hit and hospitals in New York City were overwhelmed. The national economy froze and unemployment soared; one in four American workers has applied for unemployment benefits since March. Lines of cars stretched for miles at food banks. Heavily armed lockdown protesters demonstrated across the country; in Michigan, they forced the Capitol to close and legislators to cancel their session. Nationwide, at least 100,000 people died of a disease almost no one had heard of last year.

docs.abstract: As a range of players called for unity and understanding in response to the killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis, the debate over Colin Kaepernick and his campaign for social justice resurfaced.
docs.snippet: As a range of players called for unity and understanding in response to the killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis, the debate over Colin Kaepernick and his campaign for social justice resurfaced.
docs.lead_paragraph: The outbreak of civil unrest initiated by the death of George Floyd has brought about an unusual outpouring from players, coaches and officials in the N.F.L., which has wrestled publicly with issues of race and racism more than other leagues. In some instances, however, longstanding disputes about whether the league takes the issue seriously enough have been rekindled.

headline.main: Athletes’ Outpouring on Civil Unrest Rekindles Kaepernick Debate in N.F.L.
headline.print_headline: Kaepernick Has More Allies in N.F.L., Years Later

docs.abstract: Watching “Waco” in a season of government-imposed isolation.
docs.snippet: Watching “Waco” in a season of government-imposed isolation.
docs.lead_paragraph: Midway through the fourth episode of the mini-series “Waco,” two young children are peering out one of the bullet-shattered windows of Mount Carmel, the threadbare, plywood-walled compound in which the Branch Davidian sect has barricaded itself against an army of federal agents. A young man hustles them away from the glass, then looks out himself. On the perimeter of the property, an agent from an F.B.I. tactical unit is standing on top of a tank, mooning the compound.

headline.main: A 2-Year-Old TV Series’s Accidental Pandemic Commentary
